{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> σχολή</b>, ἡ, <br /> <b>leisure, rest, ease</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “N.” 10.46, 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 3.134, etc.\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; opposed to ἀσχολία, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Politica” 1334a15, etc.\">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; σχολὴν ἄγειν to be at <b>leisure</b>, enjoy <b>ease</b>, keep <b>quiet</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus [same place], 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Medea” 1238, 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 5.29 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ἐπί τινι <b>for</b> a thing, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Apologia” 36d; περί τι Antip.Stoic. 3.256; πρός τι 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Phaedrus” 229e, 2nd c.AD: Arrianus Historicus “Epicteti Dissertationes” 1.27.15 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; τινι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd c.AD: Lucianus Sophista “Cal.” 15 \">Refs 2nd c.AD+</a>]; σ. ἀγαγεῖν ἐπί τινα to give up <b>one's time</b> to him, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “DDeor.” 12.2, etc.\">Refs</a>]; σ. ἔχειν to have <b>leisure</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Andromache” 732, 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Leges” 813c, etc.\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ἀμφὶ ἑαυτόν for one's own business, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Institutio Cyri (Cyropaedia)” 7.5.42 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; σ. ποιεῖσθαι to find leisure, πρός τι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “Mem.” 2.6.4 \">Refs</a>]: with <i>infinitive</i>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Ion” 530d \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; μὴ σχολὴν τίθει, i.e. make haste, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Agamemnon” 1059; ἡνίκ᾽ ἂν σχολὴν λάβω 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Iphigenia Taurica” 1432 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; σχολή [ἐστί] μοι I have <b>time</b>, οὐ σχολὴ αὐτῷ [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Protagoras” 314d \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; οὐκ οὔσης σ. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Plutus” 281; also παρούσης πολλῆς σ... πρός τι 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Politicus” 272b: proverbial, οὐ σ. δούλοις 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Politica” 1334a21 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: with <i>infinitive</i>, οὔτοι.. τῇδ᾽ ἐμοὶ σ. πάρα τρίβειν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Agamemnon” 1055, etc.\">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; εἴ τῳ καὶ λογίζεσθαι σ. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Ajax” 816; εἴ σοι σ. προϊόντι ἀκούειν 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Phaedrus” 227b \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; καταβαίνειν οὐ σ. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Acharnenses” 409, +others; σ. πλείων ἢ θέλω πάρεστί μοι 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Prometheus Vinctus” 818 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; σχολὴ ἐδόκει γίγνεσθαι he thought he had <b>plenty of time</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 5.10 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; σ. διδόναι, παρέχειν τινί, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Institutio Cyri (Cyropaedia)” 4.2.22, “Hier.” 10.5; σ. καταναλίσκειν εἴς τι 5th-6th c.BC: Isocrates Orator 1.18 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; τὴν τοῦ πράττοντος σ. περιμένειν to wait his <b>leisure</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 370b \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; σχολῆς τόδ᾽ ἔργον a work for <b>leisure</b>, i.e. requiring attention, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Andromache” 552: frequently with Preps., ἐπὶ σχολῆς\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>] at <b>leisure</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Theaetetus” 172d; κατὰ σχολήν 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Ecclesiazusae” 48, 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Phaedrus” 228a; μετὰ σχολῆς [prev. author] “Criti.” 110a; ὑπὸ σχολῆς 1st-2nd c.AD: Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus 2.667d; see.below 5th c.BC: Bacchylides Lyricus \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__2</b></Level3> with <i>genitive</i>, <b>leisure, rest from</b> a thing, ἔν τινι σχολῇ κακοῦ [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Tyrannus” 1286; ὡς ἂν σχολὴν λύσωμεν.. πόνων 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Hercules Furens” 725; σ. ἐστί τινι τῶν πράξεων 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Leges” 961b, compare “R.” 370c; also σ. γίγνεταί τινι ἀπό τινος [prev. author] “Phd.” 66d \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; σ. ἄγειν ἀπό τινος to keep <b>clear</b> of.., [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Institutio Cyri (Cyropaedia)” 8.3.47 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ἡ τῶν ἀναγκαίων σ. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Politica” 1269a35. \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__3</b></Level3> <b>idleness</b>, τίκτει γὰρ οὐδὲν ἐσθλὸν εἰκαία σ. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Fragmenta” 308; σ. τερπνὸν κακόν 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Hippolytus” 384. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__II</b></Level2> <b>that in which leisure is employed</b>, οὐ κάμνω σχολῇ I am not weary of <b>talk</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “Ion” 276 \">Refs</a>]; especially <b>learned discussion, disputation, lecture</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Leges” 820c (_plural_), 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Politica” 1323b39; παρεκαθίζανον.. σχολαῖς φιλομαθεῖν προαιρούμενοι “IG” 22.1011.22 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ταῦτ᾽ οὐ σχολὴ Πλάτωνο; [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd c.AD: Alexander Rhetor 158; σχολὰς ἀναγράψαι 1st c.BC: Philodemus Philosophus “Academicorum Index” p.74 M., compare 1st-2nd c.AD: Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus 2.37c, etc.; σ. περὶ πολιτείας γράψασθαι [prev. work]790e; σ. ἀναγνῶναι, λέγειν, 1st c.BC: Philodemus Philosophus “Academicorum Index” p.82 M., 2nd c.AD: Arrianus Historicus “Epicteti Dissertationes” 4.11.35 \">Refs 1st c.BC+</a>]; ἠθικαὶ σ., title of work by Persaeus, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “Stoicorum Veterum Fragmenta” 1.102, compare 1st c.BC: Cicero, M. Tullius Orator et Philosophus “Tusculanae Disputationes” 1.4.7, 8. \">Refs 1st c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.2</b></Level3> <b>a group to whom lectures were given, school</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Politica” 1313b3, 1st c.BC: Philodemus Gadarensis Epigrammaticus “Ind.Sto.” 10, 1st c.BC: Dionysius Halicarnassensis “de Isocrate” 1, “Dem.” 44, 1st-2nd c.AD: Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus “Pericles” 35, “Alex.” 7, etc.\">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; σ. ἔχειν to keep <b>a school</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd c.AD: Arrianus Historicus “Epict.” 3.21.11 \">Refs 2nd c.AD+</a>]; σχολῆς ἡγεῖσθαι to be master of <b>it</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 1st c.BC: Philodemus Philosophus “Academicorum Index” p.92 M., 1st c.BC: Dionysius Halicarnassensis “Amm.” 1.7. \">Refs 1st c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.3</b></Level3> Latin <i>schola</i>, ={σχολαστήριον}, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 1st c.BC: Vitruvius Scriptor de Architectura Latinus 5.10.4, “CIL” 10.831, etc. \">Refs 1st c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__III</b></Level2> σχολαί, αἱ, <b>regiments of the Imperial guard</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 6th c.AD: Procopius Caesariensis Historicus “de Bello Gothico” 4.27, 10th c.AD: Suidas Legal icographus \">Refs 6th c.AD+</a>] see at {διέδριον}; Latin <i>scholae,</i> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" Codex Theod. 14.17.9 (4th c.AD), etc. \">Refs 4th c.AD+</a>]<br /><Level4><b>__III.b</b></Level4> <b>section</b> of an office, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “PMasp.” 57 ii 18 (6th c.AD)\">Refs 6th c.AD+</a>]; of the [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 15 \">Refs</a>] 'schools' of shorthand writers, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 6th c.AD: Lydus, Joannes Laurentius Historicus “Mag.” 3.6. \">Refs 6th c.AD+</a>]<br /><Level1><b>__B</b></Level1> σχολῇ as <i>adverb</i>, <b>in a leisurely way, tardily</b>, ἤνυτον σ. βραδύς [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Antigone” 231, compare 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 1.142, 3.46, 5th-6th c.BC: Andocides Orator 2.19, etc.\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ἄτρεμά τε καὶ σ. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd c.AD: Alexander Rhetor 135.4; σ. καὶ βάδην 2nd c.BC: Polybius Historicus 8.28.11. \">Refs 2nd c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__B.2</b></Level3> <b>at one's leisure</b>, i.e. <b>scarcely, hardly, not at all</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Tyrannus” 434. “Ant.” 390, 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Sophista” 233b, etc.; παραινῶ πᾶσι.. σ. τεκνοῦσθαι παῖδας 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Fragmenta” 317; σ. γε 5th-6th c.BC: Andocides Orator 1.102, 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Memorabilia” 3.14.3; σ. που 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Sophista” 261 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>] b: frequently in apodosi, to introduce an <b>a fortiori</b>argument, εἰ δὲ μὴ.., ἦ που σχολῇ.. γε if not so.., <b>hardly</b> or <b>much less</b> so.., [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Andocides Orator 1.90; εἰ αὗται.. μὴ ἀκριβεῖς εἰσι, σχολῇ αἵ γε ἄλλαι 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Phaedo” 65b; εἰ μὴ τούτων.., σ. τῶν γε ἄλλων 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Metaphysica” 999a10 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ὁπότε γὰρ.., answered by σ. γε, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 610e; μὴ γιγνώσκων τὴν οὐσίαν σ. τήν γε ὀρθότητα διαγνώσεται [prev. author] “Lg.” 668c. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]","strongNumber":"G4981","accentedUnicode":"σχολή","relatedNos":[{"strongNumber":"G4980","matchingForm":"σχολάζω","stepTransliteration":"scholazō","gloss":"be devoted/empty","_zh_tw_Gloss":"空閒著, 專心","_es_Gloss":"dedicarse/estar vacío","_zh_Gloss":"空闲着, 专心"}],"shortDef":"lecture hall, a building in which students meet for discussion and study, school","mediumDef":"lecture hall, a building in which students meet for discussion and study, school <br /><b>freedom from occupation;</b>, later, <b>ease, leisure; a school,</b> <ref='Act.19.9'>Acts 19:9</ref>*","stepGloss":"lecture hall","stepTransliteration":"scholē","count":1,"_es_Definition":"salón de conferencias, escuela","_zh_tw_Definition":"演講廳 (徒 19:9)","_zh_Definition":"演讲厅 (徒 19:9)","_step_Type":"word","_vi_Definition":"trường học","_zh_tw_Gloss":"學房","_es_Gloss":"salón de conferencias","_zh_Gloss":"学房"}]}